{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/alcohol-problem-drinking/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"2aa1ce9d-21b4-5104-a4bf-15a4b8afccc5","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 1d3f94a8-2c92-4da2-92da-15a18d0066ad --><h1>Alcohol - problem drinking: Summary</h1><!-- end field 1d3f94a8-2c92-4da2-92da-15a18d0066ad -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 21952425-9d10-4b15-8e4e-6a253dd63375 --><!-- begin field 826f9464-65c3-4c19-a470-c8d4b0addd73 --><ul><li>Problem drinking is defined as regular consumption of alcohol above recommended levels.</li><li>The term 'alcohol use disorders' encompasses:<ul><li>Harmful drinking — defined as a pattern of alcohol consumption causing health problems directly related to alcohol. This could include psychological problems such as depression, alcohol-related accidents or physical illness such as acute pancreatitis</li><li>Alcohol dependence — characterised by craving, tolerance, a preoccupation with alcohol and continued drinking in spite of harmful consequences (for example, liver disease or depression caused by drinking).</li></ul></li><li>The recommended maximum alcohol intake in the UK is no more than 14 units a week for both men and women, with two or more drink-free days in the week.</li><li>For pregnant women (or women planning a pregnancy), the safest approach is not to drink alcohol at all, to minimize any risk to the fetus. </li><li>Discussions on alcohol and screening should be tailored according to the person's needs.</li><li>Formal assessment tools should be used to assess the nature and severity of alcohol misuse, including the AUDIT (Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test) for identification and as a routine measure. This can help to decide whether to offer a brief intervention or not, and if so, what type.<ul><li>If time is limited, an abbreviated version such as AUDIT-C (AUDIT-Consumption) can be used. This should be followed up with the full questionnaire if problem drinking is indicated.</li></ul></li><li>Blood tests are not recommended for the routine screening of problem drinking. However, they may help identify physical health needs relating to alcohol use.</li><li>A session of structured brief advice on alcohol should be offered to a person who is misusing alcohol. Where possible, a recognized, evidence-based resource that is based on FRAMES principles should be used:<ul><li>Feedback — on the person's risk of having alcohol problems.</li><li>Responsibility — change is the person's responsibility.</li><li>Advice — provision of clear advice when requested.</li><li>Menu — the options for change.</li><li>Empathy — an approach that is warm, reflective, and understanding.</li><li>Self-efficacy — optimism about the person's ability to change their own behaviour.</li></ul></li><li>A referral for specialist treatment should be arranged if the person has:<ul><li>Features of alcohol dependence, particularly if moderate or severe.</li><li>Failed to benefit from structured brief advice and an extended brief intervention, and wishes to receive further help.</li><li>Signs of severe alcohol-related impairment, or has a related comorbidity (e.g. liver disease or alcohol-related mental health problems).</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 826f9464-65c3-4c19-a470-c8d4b0addd73 --><!-- end item 21952425-9d10-4b15-8e4e-6a253dd63375 -->","topic":{"id":"b9a3dde8-c412-5195-8fde-5edce1ca90ef","topicId":"a79c6a40-2a77-4966-b622-3f9098a20bcc","topicName":"Alcohol - problem drinking","slug":"alcohol-problem-drinking","aliases":["Problem drinking - alcohol"],"chapters":[{"id":"2aa1ce9d-21b4-5104-a4bf-15a4b8afccc5","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"3a955db5-e8e3-5bc7-b5c8-f5940784faf3","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"03d8357e-0ebd-5b7d-8568-d7e8d49950e8","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-to